acle, from Tutankhamun and the gold of Egypt to sex in ancient literature, from the island of Lesbos (where he once lived) to the challenges of translating Ovid's wit and elegant eroticism into present-day English verse, from Victorian pederastic aesthetics to Marxism's losing battle with ancient history. This third volume of Green's essays (several previously unpublished) reveals throughout his serious concern that we are, in a very real sense, losing the legacy of antiquity through the corrosive methodologies of modern academic criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCivilization, Ancient. 0aCivilization, Classical. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aalexander.  aancient and classical literary criticism.  aancient greece and death.  aancient history.  aancient literature.  acaesar.  acatullus.  aclassical influences.  aclassical translation.  aclassicist.  adelphi.  adelphic oracle.  ademos.  ahellenistic age.  aintellectualism.  ajuvenal.  alegacy of antiquity.  alesbos.  aliterary criticism.  aliterature of antiquity.  aliterature.  ametamorphosis.  aovid.  aprecedent.  asex and classical literature.  asocrates.  astrepsiades.  asurvival.  athanatos trail.  athe genius loci.  atreasures of egypt.  atutankhamun.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020811740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918825?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918825423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918825/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY